INFO:argostranslate.utils:('paragraphs:', ['Preprint. Under review. Algorithm 1 Meerkat Require: Trace repository R = { t i } n i = 1 , natural-language safety property \u03d5 Ensure: Verdict y ЁЪ { PASS , FAIL , INCONCLUSIVE } , repository-level verdict score v , trace scores { s i } n i = 1 , candidate witness collection c W 1: { e i } n i = 1 Ёћ Represent ( R ) 2: C Ёћ Cluster ( { e i } n i = 1 ) 3: ( p , E ) Ёћ BuildInputs ( \u03d5 , R , C ) { E contains the repository and cluster structure} 4: ( v , { s i } n i = 1 , c W ) Ёћ Agent ( p , E ) 5: y Ёћ Verdict ( v ) 6: return y , v , { s i } n i = 1 , c W 2 Method overview 2.1 Problem setup Given a trace repository R = { t i } n i = 1 and a natural-language safety property \u03d5 , repository- level auditing asks whether the repository satisfies or violates \u03d5 . If it violates \u03d5 , then there must be at least one violating witness in R , formalized as a collection W \u2286 P ( R ) where each W ЁЪ W is a subset of traces whose combined evidence violates \u03d5 . The ideal output is this collection of witnesses; operationally, the auditor returns a repository-level verdict together with a score for each trace, where s ( t ) estimates the likelihood that t ЁЪ W for at least one violating witness W ЁЪ W . This framing captures both detection and localization.'])
