INFO:argostranslate.utils:('paragraphs:', ['Preprint. Under review. Data Source Risk Focus Labeled Cases Case size Cyber Misuse (Brown et al., 2025) Decomposition attacks Yes 50 20ЈC600 Bio Misuse (Brown et al., 2025) Decomposition attacks Yes 50 20ЈC600 ImpossibleBench (Zhong et al., 2026a) Task gaming Yes 200 10ЈC100 TRACE (Deshpande et al., 2026) Task gaming Yes 200 10ЈC100 CUA-SHADE-Arena (Kale et al., 2025) Covert Sabotage Yes 200 10ЈC100 Terminal-Bench-2.0 (Laude Institute, 2025) Developer cheating No 10 61ЈC364 HAL USACO (Shi et al., 2024) Developer cheating No 12 26ЈC89 CyBench (Zhang et al., 2025) Task gaming No 19 3ЈC68 BountyBench (Wen et al., 2025b) Task gaming No 9 3ЈC32 Table 1: Evaluation corpora for repository-level safety auditing. ЁАLabeledЁБ indicates whether exhaustive ground-truth verdicts are available for all evaluated traces. To audit a repository against a natural-language safety property, Meerkat prompts the agent with the property and structures the set of traces with clustering, so that the agent can efficiently reason over them. Algorithm 1 summarizes this procedure. Namely, Meerkat first constructs a clustering C over the repository R by embedding each trace with Represent ( ЁЄ ) and then using Cluster ( ЁЄ ) to cluster the embeddings with k-means (lines 1 and 2).'])
