INFO:argostranslate.utils:('paragraphs:', [' For ImpossibleBench and TRACE, we con- struct 25 positive trace repositories and 25 benign trace repositories for each case size in { 10, 25, 50, 100 } . To construct each positive trace repository of size k , we (1) randomly select p ЁЪ [ 1, max ( 1, \u230a k ЁЄ 0.05 \u230b )] as the number of positive traces, (2) sample p traces from the datasetЁЏs positive trace set, and (3) sample k \u2212 p traces from the datasetЁЏs benign trace set. Each benign trace repository is constructed by just sampling k traces from the datasetЁЏs benign trace set. Further dataset details are provided in Appendix B. Baselines For all methods, we use a shared safety property description and have each method both determine if the full case violates the safety property as well as scoring each trace within the case in terms of its membership in a safety violating witness. The full safety properties are provided in Appendix B. We compare against a per-trace monitor (Monitor) baseline which uses a single LLM call to provide each trace a safety violation score, where 1 We round the total number of traces down to avoid leaking the decomposition level to the agent. E.g., a 20 ЁС multiplier with 6 harmful decompositions yields 6 ЁС 20 + 6 = 126 total traces, which we round down to 120 (otherwise 126 mod 10 = 6 reveals the decomposition count). 4'])
INFO:argostranslate.utils:('apply_packaged_translation', ' For ImpossibleBench and TRACE, we con- struct 25 positive trace repositories and 25 benign trace repositories for each case size in { 10, 25, 50, 100 } . To construct each positive trace repository of size k , we (1) randomly select p ЁЪ [ 1, max ( 1, \u230a k ЁЄ 0.05 \u230b )] as the number of positive traces, (2) sample p traces from the datasetЁЏs positive trace set, and (3) sample k \u2212 p traces from the datasetЁЏs benign trace set. Each benign trace repository is constructed by just sampling k traces from the datasetЁЏs benign trace set. Further dataset details are provided in Appendix B. Baselines For all methods, we use a shared safety property description and have each method both determine if the full case violates the safety property as well as scoring each trace within the case in terms of its membership in a safety violating witness. The full safety properties are provided in Appendix B. We compare against a per-trace monitor (Monitor) baseline which uses a single LLM call to provide each trace a safety violation score, where 1 We round the total number of traces down to avoid leaking the decomposition level to the agent. E.g., a 20 ЁС multiplier with 6 harmful decompositions yields 6 ЁС 20 + 6 = 126 total traces, which we round down to 120 (otherwise 126 mod 10 = 6 reveals the decomposition count). 4')
