INFO:argostranslate.utils:('sentences', ['3 Bayesian scoring with clustering', 'The score-only model treats traces as exchangeable, so we use a clustering approach within each case to strengthen the baseline.', 'For each cluster c , we compute a campaign score p clust ( c ) from five normalized features: cluster size f size ( c ) , mean pairwise cosine similarity f coh ( c ) , within-cluster concentration of nonzero scores relative to the case-wide background f conc ( c ) , maximum trace score f max ( c ) , and mean trace score f mean ( c ) .', 'We combine them as p clust ( c ) = 0.25 f size ( c ) + 0.25 f coh ( c ) + 0.25 f conc ( c ) + 0.15 f max ( c ) + 0.10 f mean ( c ) , (6) and then merge the cluster score with the scores as: \u02c6 p i = 1 \u2212 ( 1 \u2212 p i )( 1 \u2212 p clust ( c )) . (7)', 'Our default hyperparameters are bucket width b = 0.1, smoothing constant a = 1.0, stabilization passes K = 5, and benign prior Іа 0 = 0.5.', 'Ablation.', 'To isolate the effect of clustering, we compare the full method against a Bayesian approach that only uses the per-trace scores.', 'Table 14 reports leave-one-out results.', 'The raw Bayesian updating yields no improvement, because the monitor scores most traces as zero, and benign and malicious score distributions overlap heavily.', 'Adding cluster boosting improves AUROC by 0.08ЈC0.20 by exploiting the fact that malicious traces tend to form small, semantically coherent groups.', '34'])
